$interpreted: Tingko: Wh-What's going on here?
Jiyanama: Is that Lord Juan Yun!? Why are you carrying the princess...?
Juan Yun: Hello, ladies. Don't worry, it's not what you think... probably...
Tingko: Eh? Ehhhhhhh!?
Tindoiimu: ...Lord Juan Yun loves to joke around, as always.
Tindoiimu: I twisted my ankle. Juan Yun offered his assistance. Help me down.
Jiyanama: Oh princess, really, how on earth did you twist your ankle?
Tindoiimu: I wasn't paying attention and slid down from the roof...
Tindoiimu: Thank you for your help. A lucky coincidence that you happened to be nearby.
Juan Yun: Coincidence? Maybe I just wanted to see you~
Tindoiimu: .........
Juan Yun: Well it has been a while. You know, you're allowed to joke around sometimes, too, princess.
Juan Yun: Really, though, I saw Himawari come through here looking mad, so I came to make sure everything was OK.
Juan Yun: But as you know, I'm not the fastest qilin in the east...
Juan Yun: Haha...
Tindoiimu: ...There was just a misunderstanding with Himawari. She's very protective of you, you know.
Tindoiimu: Everything is fine, Juan Yun.
Juan Yun: It's not fine, though. I know what that must have been about—it's my fault, really.
Tindoiimu: I appreciate your concern, Juan Yun. But please don't worry about it.
Juan Yun: Yeah? Well, that's a load off...
Juan Yun: I was worried there'd be no way you'd agree to this. Then, let me ask you formally.
Juan Yun: —Princess Tindoiimu, I, Lord Juan Yun of the Qilin Tribe, formally invite you to serve as shaman for the Wind Sect.
Tindoiimu: Wait... Wh-What? So Himawari was...
Juan Yun: The Peace Ceremony is to celebrate peace, and you, princess, represent the Alliance's peaceful relationship with the Insect Tribe.
Juan Yun: I couldn't think of a more suitable wind shaman.
Tindoiimu: ...Lord Juan Yun, I know you love to tell jokes, but this is too much...
Juan Yun: Eh? I'm actually completely serious. Why would I joke about this...?
Tindoiimu: Then let me stop this right here. No, I cannot accept your invitation.
Juan Yun: And why is that?
Tindoiimu: I am an insignificant political hostage, not suited to fill such a high position.
Tindoiimu: What's more, the Wind Sect will hold the ceremony this year. Which means even more eyes will be on the wind shaman.
Juan Yun: You're overthinking it. You are princess of the Insect Tribe, bestowed with such natural beauty. Who could be more fitting?
Tindoiimu: (It's not that easy... this guy is so naive...)
Tindoiimu: I am truly not worthy of your kind words, but... I sprained my ankle...
Juan Yun: That's no problem—There's plenty of time before the ceremony. Rest up first. We'll talk about everything else later.
Juan Yun: Well then, It's getting late. I'll see you all later~
Tingko: Uh, does he really not get it, or is this some kind of long con?
Tingko: Princess, you've got to tell that guy "no way"!
Jiyanama: What do you know? She is showing him respect. Now quit complaining and tend to the princess' ankle!
Tindoiimu: No need. I did it on purpose.
Tindoiimu: I was worried that Himawari was serious, so I twisted it just in case. Didn't think it'd come in handy so soon.
Tingko: ... I'm just afraid that even after taking such extreme measures, he still won't give up.
Jiyanama: Hmph... that child does nothing but joke. Why would this time be any different? I bet he's already forgotten about it.
Tingko: That would be great, but it doesn't change the princess' ankle situation...
Juan Yun: Hello~ Didn't mean to scare you—I was in the area and thought I would come check up on the princess' ankle.
Tindoiimu: ...Welcome. It hasn't healed completely, but it does seem to be a bit better.
Juan Yun: Fantastic! See, you'll be great as shaman~
Tindoiimu: Well, the physician says that I should really stay off of it for a while longer. I think Himawari will have to be shaman this time.
Juan Yun: I see. Okay, then~ I'll think it over, but don't you go giving up on me, now!
Juan Yun: I'll see you soon.
Tindoiimu: ...You mean you're going to come back?
Juan Yun: Naturally.
Juan Yun: Even a day without you seems like a lifetime, princess.
Tindoiimu: .........
Tingko: He comes everyday. I feel tired for Tindoiimu just watching.
Jiyanama: Perhaps he is serious.
Tingko: You mean he seriously loves causing trouble?
Jiyanama: You... you are much too inexperienced...
Tindoiimu: Lord Juan Yun, I thank you for the invitation... but by now you must know what I think about the matter.
Juan Yun: The heart is like a drifting cloud, ever-changing. A sincere heart can bend even metal and stone.
Juan Yun: So, I shall return tomorrow~
Jiyanama: Hmph, clingy men... an independent woman's worst nightmare.
Tingko: Princess, that guy's seriously a pain. You got to give him a piece of your mind!
Tingko: Really make him cry! There's no way he'd bother you after that.
Tindoiimu: Oh Ting... you should know there's some people you just can't defy. Life's more complicated...
Tindoiimu: And "make him cry"? That's not something Tingko would usually say. She didn't ask Jihasaha, did she...?
Tindoiimu: *sigh* So you both can't think of anything, huh?
Juan Yun: Why not tell me what's on your mind? Maybe I could think of something~
Tindoiimu: What are you doing here!?
Juan Yun: Whoa, whoa~ I come in peace! I surely wasn't following you or anything...
Juan Yun: Actually... well, it's a long story.
Tindoiimu: Make it short, then.
Juan Yun: Well, the moon was looking so beautiful, so I wanted to share it with someone just as stunning. And Tingko said you went out, so...
Juan Yun: It must be fate that I've found you here. I thought, with me being so slow and all...
Juan Yun: Speaking of which... your ankle seems to be doing much better?
Tindoiimu: ...Not yet... You must be mistaken.
Juan Yun: But I can see it right now. It's clearly—
Tindoiimu: Enough! Lord Juan Yun, how long do you wish to push me so—
Juan Yun: Watch out!
Juan Yun: Who are you!?
Assassin: Die, maggot!
Juan Yun: Don't you run away!
Tindoiimu: Don't chase them. They've surely prepared an escape route.
Tindoiimu: Who dares intrude on qilin land so boldy, attacking their lord?
Tindoiimu: What if they were even more determined, unafraid to die? Would you be able to stop them then?
Juan Yun: I... Indeed, that was a close call...
Juan Yun: I'm too slow... not the most skilled martial artist.
Tindoiimu: But you still tried to protect me?
Tindoiimu: That assassin was clearly heading towards me.
Juan Yun: A pretty girl in trouble—how could I not help?
Tindoiimu: I wasn't joking.
Juan Yun: .........
Juan Yun: ...I'm serious.
Juan Yun: Or maybe the princess thinks my handicap disqualifies me from rescuing damsels in distress?
Tindoiimu: ...No, I didn't mean—Please, don't take it that way, Lord Juan Yun.
Juan Yun: Oh stop, I'm just kidding~
Juan Yun: I know what you're thinking. You think the Qilin Tribe sent these assassins on purpose?
Tindoiimu: You...
Juan Yun: I may be slow, but I did pick up on that.
Tindoiimu: ...No, I wouldn't dare. That's not...
Tindoiimu: It's just that as a political hostage, I'm worried that, if I died, no one would be able to hold back the fires of war any longer.
Juan Yun: The princess' temperament is just like her injury—changing so fast, I can't keep up!
Tindoiimu: .........
Tindoiimu: (What nonsense, my ankle healed days ago...)
Juan Yun: So you think some of us want another war, huh?

Juan Yun: ...It's true. The Alliance is formed by various eastern tribes.

Even though a peace treaty has been established, it's hard for some people to forget past feuds.
Juan Yun: Besides that, there's also a lot to gain from war...
Tindoiimu: ...You see quite clearly, my lord.
Juan Yun: Princess, these matters pain me so. Something as obvious as this, and yet I need the princess to remind me.
Tindoiimu: ...In name, I am a guest here. But in essence... a hostage.
Tindoiimu: If I serve as the wind shaman and a dispute arises as a result, it may be used as an excuse for war.
Tindoiimu: I cannot bear to think of what may happen...
Tindoiimu: Since I came to the East Alliance at eleven years old, I've only wished to live in peace... I wish you the best, my lord.
Juan Yun: ...I understand.
Tindoiimu: Thank you...
Juan Yun: So, if the people agree that you are a guest of the Qilin Tribe and not a hostage, then there should be no issue, right?
Tindoiimu: ...Huh? N-No, that's not what I meant...
Juan Yun: Princess Tindoiimu, allow me to see you home, will you?
